english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion by the Pool at Suwon
  author: Lee Saeк
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A pool, terraces, slopes, and pavilions—these are places for leisure and wandering. What have they to do with the governance of the world? And yet the rise and fall of kingdoms, the flourishing and decline of provinces and counties—all of these are inscribed here.

    When the court is clear and luminous, and peace settles above and below, officials find joy in their duties and the people rest content in their lives. Without pools and pavilions, slopes and gazebos, how could we paint the splendor of an era of great peace? But when laws grow harsh and exactions heavy, when taxes burden the land with their weight, the people lament in the fields and officials suffer in their offices. Even with pools and pavilions, slopes and gazebos, can any of us find solace alone?

    Then how could the new pavilion of Suwon be left without a record?

    In the northeast corner of Suwon, there once lay an ancient pool, long fallen into ruin and neglect. When Lord Jeon Seongan came to govern the region, he gazed upon the desolation with a troubled heart and resolved to restore it. He deepened the waters and raised an island at its center, upon which the new pavilion would stand—graceful as a bird in flight. Yet no resources came from the public coffers, and no labor was demanded of the common people.

    When at last the work was complete, the people of the town beheld it with astonishment. They turned to one another in wonder, saying: "How was this accomplished so swiftly? Surely some divine hand must have guided it! We were never called to toil, and yet behold what has been made!" Ah, Lord Jeon truly understood the art of employing the people.

    Shortly after, Lord Jeon was transferred to the capital. It was then that Lord An, serving as Inspector of the Secretariat, came to oversee the region of Yangguang. Admiring Lord Jeon's able administration, he sent word to me: "The deeds of Lord Jeon must not fade away. Let them be passed to posterity through your brush. Do not refuse this task."

    I reflected thus: Suwon, governed by the provincial administration, holds dominion over many counties and represents the convergence of culture for the entire region. Yet its fortune or misfortune, its flourishing or decline, sets the standard for all the region. Now Lord Jeon brings both authority and compassion to his rule, gathering and settling all with perfect measure—never burdening the humble folk, but spreading forth the beauty of our nation's great peace. As for Lord An, his station calls him to observe the customs of the people, and he delights in speaking of the virtues of others. All of this is worthy of record.

    Should I in later days, having completed my service, retire and pass through this town again, if fortune brings me to see the lotus blossoms in bloom, I shall surely halt my carriage and climb to this pavilion. There I shall read these words I have written, and only then depart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'pool and pavilion' (池臺) serves as a metaphor throughout this text for the stability and prosperity of a well-governed state. The literary device suggests that public works reflecting harmony between government and people are manifestations of good governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'lotus blossoms' (荷花) carries symbolic weight in East Asian poetry, often representing purity, enlightenment, and the ideal conditions of a harmonious realm.
